<DOC><DOCNO> AP890726-0230 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-07-26-89 1357EDT</FILEID><FIRST>a n AM-ReligionRdp Adv28   07-26 0650</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Religion Rdp, Adv 28,0675</SECOND><HEAD>$Adv28</HEAD><HEAD>For Release Fri AMs, July 28 and Thereafter</HEAD><DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The youth department of the Church of God inChrist, a predominantly black Pentecostal group, has set itspriority into the next century on fighting drugs and called onother churches for help.   The program was launched at the annual convention of thechurch's United National Auxiliaries. The denomination claims 3million members in the United States and some 1.5 million in 44other countries.   ``We hope to make an impact across the country,'' said BishopCharles Brewer of New Haven, Conn., chairman of the youthdepartment.   A drug enforcement agent for east-central states, N. JohnWilder, told the convention, ``Drug addiction is not only a socialproblem, it is a spiritual problem,''   Bishop Floyd Perry of Cleveland said, ``When those who areaddicted leave treatment centers they often go back to drugs, andwe have to change that, we have to stop that.   ``Treatment is the Bandaid, it only patches up the problem, butthe churches must do the healing...Our 6,000 churches are going tosend a message out about drugs that the real permanent answer isspiritual faith, and we intend to cross denominational lines withthat message.''</TEXT><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The divorce rate among Jews who intermarry _ 32percent _is much higher than for marriages between Jews _ 17percent, a study finds.   The study by the North American Jewish Data Bank at the GraduateSchool of the City University of New York also found that divorcedJews who remarry are three times more likely to intermarry thanthose marrying a first time.</TEXT><DATELINE>MANILA, the Phillipines (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   China will reflect ``ideologicalpluralism'' by the century's end, predicts Jonathan Chao, head ofthe Chinese Research Center in Hong Kong.   Chao, who has examined the ups and downs of freedom andoppression in China since 1842, told the Lausannne II InternationalCongress on World Evangelism: ``Whether it will come by civil waror by peaceful reform, I don't know, but it will come.''</TEXT><DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   A draft of a universal Roman Catholiccatechism is expected to be ready by November, says ArchbishopWilliam J. Levada of Portland, Ore.   Levada, a member of the catechism's drafting committee set upafter the catechism was asked by a 1985 Synod of Bishops in Rome,made his comment on a syndicated religious television program.</TEXT><DATELINE>BALTIMORE (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Archbishop John L., May of St. Louis, presidentof the National Conference of Catholic Bishops, addresses theKnights of Columbus convention here Aug. 1-3.   About 2,000 delegates of the 1.5-million-member Catholicfraternal service organization and their wives are expected toattend.</TEXT><DATELINE>SAN JUAN, Texas (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   After converging here late this week, aconvoy of 27 supply-laden trucks called the ``Pastors for Peace''caravan was scheduled to head for Nicaragua to help meet needs ofits people.   Driving a pickup truck loaded with items ranging from medicalsupplies to musical instruments, the Rev. Robert Holmes of Helena,Mont., a retired United Methodist minister, said:   ``It's a cooperative venture and an effort to build bridges withpeople we do not believe are in any way a threat to the UnitedStates.''   The convoy, sponsored by the Interreligious Foundation forCommunity Organization, is carrying an estimated $1 million worthof goods for Nicaraguan people deprived by ravages of civil war andhurricane.   The trucks, which began their trip from scattered points in thecountry before merging here, was scheduled to reach Managua Aug. 11.   Doug Colter of Chelsea, N. Y., driver of a truckload of farmequipment, supplies for craft industry and developing commericalfishing for El Salvadoran refugees in Nicaragua, said of the convoy:   ``It makes a statement that there are people in this country whocare about the Nicaraguans' life situation.''</TEXT><NOTE>End Adv for Fri AMs, July 28</NOTE></DOC>